 =20
If you work at an investment bank, at some point early in your career you w=
ill be told the inspirational story of The Banker Who Told The Client Not T=
o Do The Deal. This legendary banker was approached by a valued client abou=
t buying another company. The client wanted to do the deal, and would pay t=
he bank a big fee for doing it, which would result in a big bonus for The B=
anker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal. The deal could easily be done=
. But=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal took a look at=
 the financials and the business logic and said to the client =E2=80=9Cno, =
client, you will be better off not doing the deal.=E2=80=9D The client relu=
ctantly agreed. The=C2=A0bank missed out on the fee. But the client respect=
ed the bank, and it especially respected The Banker Who Told The Client Not=
 To Do The Deal, who became a trusted adviser to the client forever. Later =
it turned out that the deal would have been bad, and=C2=A0The Banker Who To=
ld The Client Not To Do The Deal saved the client from a costly mistake.[10=
]=C2=A0Later the client did lots of other, bigger deals, and always paid th=
e bank big fees for advising on them.This is an inspirational story designe=
d to drive home the message that you should always do the right thing for t=
he client, be long-term greedy, keep the client=E2=80=99s interests in mind=
 instead of your grubby fee, etc. But the fact that it is told with such re=
verence suggests that it is, you know, unusual. Most of the time, if a clie=
nt really wants to do a deal, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Cwell, it's their=
 money, I am just a service provider.=E2=80=9D Also, most of the time,=C2=
=A0if a client really wants to do a deal and you say =E2=80=9Cno, don=E2=80=
=99t do that deal,=E2=80=9D the client will not respect you; the client wil=
l be like =E2=80=9Cthis banker doesn=E2=80=99t understand my rare business =
genius=E2=80=9D and will just hire someone else. Also, most of the time, yo=
ur interactions with clients are=C2=A0largely about=C2=A0pitching them=C2=
=A0deals; it would be weird to turn around and say =E2=80=9Cactually never =
mind don=E2=80=99t do that deal.=E2=80=9D Also, if you tell a client not to=
 do a deal that would bring in a big fee, maybe in 10 years you will be spo=
ken of in tones of hushed reverence=C2=A0as=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The Cl=
ient Not To Do The Deal, but meanwhile you won=E2=80=99t bring in the big f=
ee and your bonus will be lower. Future tones of hushed reverence won=E2=80=
=99t buy you a beach house.Anyway General Electric Co. is maybe the best in=
vestment banking client in the world because it does so many deals. In part=
icular it did a lot of deals to build a big conglomerate, and then it did a=
 lot of deals to dismantle the big conglomerate, with more coming now as it=
 plans to=C2=A0break=C2=A0up into three pieces. Bankers rarely said no:Gene=
ral Electric has paid more than $7bn in investment banking fees since 2000,=
 as Wall Street lenders reaped rewards from a frenzied period of dealmaking=
 that culminated in a sinking share price and the eventual break-up of the =
best-known US conglomerate. =E2=80=A6Since 2000, the company has shelled ou=
t more on investment banking fees than any other US business, according to =
the Refinitiv figures. The next biggest spenders were Citi and JPMorgan, wh=
ich paid their bankers $6.8bn, while the biggest outlay at an industrial gr=
oup was GM, which spent $3.8bn.Critics=E2=80=89have said the outsized fees =
are indicative of how bankers =E2=80=94 who have profited despite GE=E2=80=
=99s market value falling about 75 per cent since 2000 =E2=80=94 care more =
about completing lucrative transactions than acting in the best interests o=
f their clients.=E2=80=9CGE has been on an acquiring spree for more than 20=
 years, with disastrous outcomes,=E2=80=9D said Nuno Fernandes, professor o=
f finance at IESE Business School.Fernandes added: =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s=
 a pernicious conflict of interest here=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89. Becau=
se investment banks receive much larger fees when the deals are closed, ban=
kers were always on the side of completing as many deals as possible, not o=
n GE=E2=80=99s side.=E2=80=9DI dunno, I would not call it a =E2=80=9Cpernic=
ious conflict of interest.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s like, GE wanted deals, so =
it went to the deal-executers and said =E2=80=9Cexecute these deals for us =
and we=E2=80=99ll pay you,=E2=80=9D and the deal-executers executed the dea=
ls and cashed the checks. They=C2=A0could have=C2=A0said no, but it would h=
ave been kind of a weird move.
