s to file a Form 4, so I guess it=E2=80=99s theoretically possible that he =
exercised options and sold options shares under his Rule 10b5-1 plan on Tue=
sday and Wednesday and hasn=E2=80=99t yet disclosed that. It would be *very=
* weird, though, since he has already disclosed millions of shares of non-1=
0b5-1 sales on those days; why would he disclose some early and wait on oth=
ers?[5] Note that 2.15 million shares a week *isn=E2=80=99t fast enough*: I=
f he wants to exercise all 22.9 million shares by the end of 2021, to avoid=
 a tax increase next year, he=E2=80=99s only got eight weeks; he=E2=80=99d =
need to do about 2.9 million a week.[6] This would be a very weird thing fo=
r the plan to say, given that he put it in place in mid-September when the =
stock was in the $700s; =E2=80=9Csell stock only if it=E2=80=99s up more th=
an 50%=E2=80=9D is not normal a way make sure all your options get exercise=
d. Maybe it=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9Cexercise 2.15 million options per day u=
nless the stock closed down more than X% the previous day,=E2=80=9D I dunno=
.[7] One other point about the 10b5-1 plan is that it=E2=80=99s not clear t=
hat it=E2=80=99s *necessary*. In general, if you are the chief executive of=
ficer of a public company there are not a lot of open windows when you can =
sell stock. But Musk is in one: Tesla  announced its third-quarter earnings=
 on Oct. 20, and it=E2=80=99s still 50-odd days from the end of the fourth =
quarter. And so Musk was able to sell stock on Tuesday and Wednesday *witho=
ut* a prearranged plan. He could have done the options that way too. It=E2=
=80=99s still best practice=C2=A0to do the 10b5-1 plan: In September, he kn=
ew he=E2=80=99d need to exercise the options, but he didn=E2=80=99t know if=
 he=E2=80=99d have material nonpublic information in November and December,=
 so it was a good idea to set up an automatic exercise/sales plan to make s=
ure he=E2=80=99d be able to sell. And if the plan does involve selling over=
 the entire remaining quarter, eventually he=E2=80=99ll go into a blackout =
period (near the end of the quarter) and then the 10b5-1 plan will be neces=
sary. But this week, he could have just freely exercised options and sold s=
tock without a 10b5-1 plan.[8] For what it=E2=80=99s worth, I think that ev=
en if Musk completely ignored the results of the poll and did the opposite =
of what his Twitter voters wanted, you=E2=80=99d have a tough time making o=
ut a case of securities fraud, though I have no doubt that someone would tr=
y.[9] A third possible answer=C2=A0is: No, Elon Musk knows what he is doing=
, he knows his audience on Twitter, he phrased the poll the way he did, the=
re was no way that the poll would have gone the other way, he knew that, an=
d he was confident that he=E2=80=99d be selling on Monday with the blessing=
 of his Twitter followers.[10] In some versions of the story, the client do=
es the deal anyway with another bank, the other bank gets the fee,=C2=A0the=
 deal is a disaster, the client regrets it, and *then* the client respects =
and trusts=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal forever.[=
11] These numbers are a little fuzzy. The $875 million comes from the annou=
ncement of the deal: =E2=80=9CThe transaction values Trump Media & Technolo=
gy Group at an initial enterprise value of $875 Million.=E2=80=9D The merge=
r agreement (which I  discussed here) reveals that what this means is that =
TMTG=E2=80=99s current shareholders (presumably Trump and others)=C2=A0will=
 get a number of shares in the post-SPAC company equal to $875 million divi=
ded by the trust value per share of the SPAC, which is $10.20, meaning that=
 they get about 85.8 million shares for their company. They also get up to =
40 million =E2=80=9Cearnout=E2=80=9D shares if the stock price is above $30=
 consistently; it=E2=80=99s been above $50 basically since the deal was ann=
ounced, so I=E2=80=99m crediting them with the full earnout. So they get 12=
5.8 million shares of the combined company. The shares of the SPAC trade cl=
osed yesterday at $58.30. So TMTG=E2=80=99s shares are worth about $7.33 bi=
llion. I should say that these numbers are not quite fair. If you buy in at=
 $58.30 per share, and then the stock *drops* to $10 and stays there, you d=
idn=E2=80=99t *really* buy in at a $7=C2=A0billion valuation: TMTG=E2=80=99=
s shareholders won=E2=80=99t get the earnout, they=E2=80=99ll end up with o=
nly 85.8 million shares, and your entry valuation was effectively $5 billio=
n.[12]=C2=A0Yes, it happened in Lucid, though that was a little different i=
n that the PIPE was signed at the same time as the SPAC deal. (The SPAC was=
 just trading at ridiculous levels pre-deal.) But, yeah:  Lucid was a reall=
y weird deal!=C2=A0
