<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Banking fees</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you work at an investment bank, at =
some point early in your career you will be told the inspirational story of=
 The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal. This legendary banker w=
as approached by a valued client about buying another company. The client w=
anted to do the deal, and would pay the bank a big fee for doing it, which =
would result in a big bonus for The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do Th=
e Deal. The deal could easily be done. But=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The Cli=
ent Not To Do The Deal took a look at the financials and the business logic=
 and said to the client =E2=80=9Cno, client, you will be better off not doi=
ng the deal.=E2=80=9D The client reluctantly agreed. The=C2=A0bank missed o=
ut on the fee. But the client respected the bank, and it especially respect=
ed The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal, who became a trusted =
adviser to the client forever. Later it turned out that the deal would have=
 been bad, and=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal saved=
 the client from a costly mistake.[10]=C2=A0Later the client did lots of ot=
her, bigger deals, and always paid the bank big fees for advising on them.<=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is an inspirational story designed to =
drive home the message that you should always do the right thing for the cl=
ient, be long-term greedy, keep the client=E2=80=99s interests in mind inst=
ead of your grubby fee, etc. But the fact that it is told with such reveren=
ce suggests that it is, you know, unusual. Most of the time, if a client re=
ally wants to do a deal, you=E2=80=99re like =E2=80=9Cwell, it's their mone=
y, I am just a service provider.=E2=80=9D Also, most of the time,=C2=A0if a=
 client really wants to do a deal and you say =E2=80=9Cno, don=E2=80=99t do=
 that deal,=E2=80=9D the client will not respect you; the client will be li=
ke =E2=80=9Cthis banker doesn=E2=80=99t understand my rare business genius=
=E2=80=9D and will just hire someone else. Also, most of the time, your int=
eractions with clients are=C2=A0largely about=C2=A0<em>pitching them=C2=A0<=
/em>deals; it would be weird to turn around and say =E2=80=9Cactually never=
 mind don=E2=80=99t do that deal.=E2=80=9D Also, if you tell a client not t=
o do a deal that would bring in a big fee, maybe in 10 years you will be sp=
oken of in tones of hushed reverence=C2=A0as=C2=A0The Banker Who Told The C=
lient Not To Do The Deal, but meanwhile you won=E2=80=99t bring in the big =
fee and your bonus will be lower. Future tones of hushed reverence won=E2=
=80=99t buy you a beach house.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Gener=
al Electric Co. is maybe the best investment banking client in the world be=
cause it does so many deals. In particular it did a lot of deals to build a=
 big conglomerate, and then it did a lot of deals to dismantle the big cong=
lomerate, with more coming now as it plans to=C2=A0break=C2=A0up into three=
 pieces. Bankers <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
5665904.269658/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZmE3MTk1NzQtYjQ1Ny00M2Zk=
LTljNDUtYWUxOWE1MTBjMWNi/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6866ac77" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">rarely =
said no</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">General Electric h=
as paid more than $7bn in investment banking fees since 2000, as Wall Stree=
t lenders reaped rewards from a frenzied period of dealmaking that culminat=
ed in a sinking share price and the eventual break-up of the best-known US =
conglomerate. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Since 2000, the com=
pany has shelled out more on investment banking fees than any other US busi=
ness, according to the Refinitiv figures. The next biggest spenders were Ci=
ti and JPMorgan, which paid their bankers $6.8bn, while the biggest outlay =
at an industrial group was GM, which spent $3.8bn.</p><p style=3D"margin: 1=
6px 0;">Critics=E2=80=89have said the outsized fees are indicative of how b=
ankers =E2=80=94 who have profited despite GE=E2=80=99s market value fallin=
g about 75 per cent since 2000 =E2=80=94 care more about completing lucrati=
ve transactions than acting in the best interests of their clients.</p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CGE has been on an acquiring spree for mor=
e than 20 years, with disastrous outcomes,=E2=80=9D said Nuno Fernandes, pr=
ofessor of finance at IESE Business School.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"=
>Fernandes added: =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s a pernicious conflict of interes=
t here=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89. Because investment banks receive much =
larger fees when the deals are closed, bankers were always on the side of c=
ompleting as many deals as possible, not on GE=E2=80=99s side.=E2=80=9D</p>=
</blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I dunno, I would not call it a =
=E2=80=9Cpernicious conflict of interest.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s like, GE wa=
nted deals, so it went to the deal-executers and said =E2=80=9Cexecute thes=
e deals for us and we=E2=80=99ll pay you,=E2=80=9D and the deal-executers e=
xecuted the deals and cashed the checks. They=C2=A0<em>could have=C2=A0</em=
>said no, but it would have been kind of a weird move.</p><table class=3D"l=
iveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" align=
=3D"center">
