ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
get two business days to file a Form 4</a>, so I guess it=E2=80=99s theoret=
ically possible that he exercised options and sold options shares under his=
 Rule 10b5-1 plan on Tuesday and Wednesday and hasn=E2=80=99t yet disclosed=
 that. It would be *very* weird, though, since he has already disclosed mil=
lions of shares of non-10b5-1 sales on those days; why would he disclose so=
me early and wait on others?</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[5] N=
ote that 2.15 million shares a week *isn=E2=80=99t fast enough*: If he want=
s to exercise all 22.9 million shares by the end of 2021, to avoid a tax in=
crease next year, he=E2=80=99s only got eight weeks; he=E2=80=99d need to d=
o about 2.9 million a week.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[6] Th=
is would be a very weird thing for the plan to say, given that he put it in=
 place in mid-September when the stock was in the $700s; =E2=80=9Csell stoc=
k only if it=E2=80=99s up more than 50%=E2=80=9D is not normal a way make s=
ure all your options get exercised. Maybe it=E2=80=99s like =E2=80=9Cexerci=
se 2.15 million options per day unless the stock closed down more than X% t=
he previous day,=E2=80=9D I dunno.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em=
>[7] One other point about the 10b5-1 plan is that it=E2=80=99s not clear t=
hat it=E2=80=99s *necessary*. In general, if you are the chief executive of=
ficer of a public company there are not a lot of open windows when you can =
sell stock. But Musk is in one: Tesla <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomber=
gbusiness.com/click/25665904.269658/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9=
lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEzMTg2MDUvMDAwMTU2NDU5MDIxMDUxMzA3L3RzbGEtZXg5OTFfODUuaHRt/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBfc6bae8f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> announced its third-quarter earn=
ings</a> on Oct. 20, and it=E2=80=99s still 50-odd days from the end of the=
 fourth quarter. And so Musk was able to sell stock on Tuesday and Wednesda=
y *without* a prearranged plan. He could have done the options that way too=
. It=E2=80=99s still best practice=C2=A0to do the 10b5-1 plan: In September=
, he knew he=E2=80=99d need to exercise the options, but he didn=E2=80=99t =
know if he=E2=80=99d have material nonpublic information in November and De=
cember, so it was a good idea to set up an automatic exercise/sales plan to=
 make sure he=E2=80=99d be able to sell. And if the plan does involve selli=
ng over the entire remaining quarter, eventually he=E2=80=99ll go into a bl=
ackout period (near the end of the quarter) and then the 10b5-1 plan will b=
e necessary. But this week, he could have just freely exercised options and=
 sold stock without a 10b5-1 plan.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em=
>[8] For what it=E2=80=99s worth, I think that even if Musk completely igno=
red the results of the poll and did the opposite of what his Twitter voters=
 wanted, you=E2=80=99d have a tough time making out a case of securities fr=
aud, though I have no doubt that someone would try.</em></p><p style=3D"mar=
gin: 16px 0;"><em>[9] A third possible answer=C2=A0is: No, Elon Musk knows =
what he is doing, he knows his audience on Twitter, he phrased the poll the=
 way he did, there was no way that the poll would have gone the other way, =
he knew that, and he was confident that he=E2=80=99d be selling on Monday w=
ith the blessing of his Twitter followers.</em></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;"><em>[10] In some versions of the story, the client does the deal anywa=
y with another bank, the other bank gets the fee,=C2=A0the deal is a disast=
er, the client regrets it, and *then* the client respects and trusts=C2=A0T=
he Banker Who Told The Client Not To Do The Deal forever.</em></p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[11] These numbers are a little fuzzy. The $875 mi=
llion comes from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/2=
5665904.269658/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4NDk2=
MzUvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTIxMTI4MjMyL3RtMjEzMDcyNGQxX2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b852=
